  "accepted_findings": [
    "Doubling LeafBaseColorScale produces the strongest independent green-response increase in both corridor views.",
    "Neutral-white transmission alone changes fewer pixels and does not materially reduce the river-eye dark-crown fraction.",
    "The combined control produces a measurable interaction, raising crown-mask green classification to 28.33 percent in guide-seat and 37.46 percent in river-eye.",
    "All modes retain identical 1,200-tree placement counts, fixed saved lighting, neutral AO/normals/emissive, and unchanged physics authority."
  ],
  "rejection_reasons": [
    "Even the combined control remains visually near-black at gameplay distance and leaves 43.91 percent of guide-seat and 71.78 percent of river-eye crown-mask pixels dark.",
    "The combined mode changes two physical controls simultaneously and cannot identify whether the remaining loss belongs to the TwoSidedFoliage shading model.",
    "Four-times opacity remains visually close to solid cards and does not preserve credible leaf-edge breakup.",
    "None of the V19 modes makes the sparse single-species corridor lifelike or production-ready."
  ],
  "next_iteration_requirements": [
    "Build a diagnostic masked DefaultLit leaf material from the same textures and opacity graph, with identical 1.18 and 2.36 base-color variants.",
    "Compare DefaultLit to TwoSidedFoliage under the saved corridor rig to isolate shading-model response from texture reflectance.",
    "Keep diagnostic materials in the review path and retain neutral production defaults until a physically plausible response is selected.",
    "Then lower opacity amplification and validate leaf-shaped breakup before adding mixed native ecology."
  ]
}
